Cell["\<\
Functions are expressions which have single dependent variable (y) for any \
defined value of the independent variable (x). The interval which independent \
variable spans is called ``Domain\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] and related \
dependent variable interval ``Range\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote].\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765952020017226*^9, 3.765952151922881*^9}, {
  3.765953096168653*^9, 3.76595310382425*^9}, {3.7659531342718663`*^9, 
  3.765953293400981*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1ec96b99-d340-40e9-b1fa-\
e9fc14c48232"],

Cell["\<\
Every function give a single dependent variable (y) value, for any defined \
value of the independent variable (x). This constitutes an {x,y} point in 2D \
projection surface. That means functions produce a distinct point in a 2D \
area per defined values of the independent vaiable. We can explore these \
points using Table [ ] function of Mathematica.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765953317613158*^9, 3.7659533507052546`*^9}, {
   3.765953383354609*^9, 3.7659534724327354`*^9}, {3.765953502493568*^9, 
   3.7659536554612203`*^9}, {3.7659537036447*^9, 3.7659537321614046`*^9}, 
   3.7668383182120895`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"c8182e80-d5b3-486e-bd0a-\
e44930b7571c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"t1", " ", "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"2", " ", 
       SuperscriptBox["x", "2"], " ", 
       RowBox[{"Exp", "[", 
        RowBox[{"-", "x"}], "]"}], 
       RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "x", "]"}]}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"x", ",", " ", "0", ",", "20", ",", "0.02"}], "}"}]}], "]"}], "//",
     "N"}]}], ";"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7659079375355825`*^9, 3.7659080176676025`*^9}, {
  3.765953862509971*^9, 3.7659538666546025`*^9}, {3.765955123174463*^9, 
  3.765955123532258*^9}, {3.765955194102955*^9, 3.765955207048561*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[16]:=",ExpressionUUID->"440b8964-7c63-4c4f-a855-5e55bdb2db06"],

Cell["\<\
We can plot g[x] in the domain of x [0,20] with increments of 2, that will \
give the mapping of the points of t1 in 2D space. The procedure is explained \
in our paper \.b4\.b4ScatterPlot.pdf\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote].\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765953906248989*^9, 3.765954073709346*^9}, {
  3.7659541139573708`*^9, 3.765954114901819*^9}, {3.765954166049611*^9, 
  3.765954245706117*^9}, {3.7659543550616636`*^9, 3.765954395258727*^9}, {
  3.765954436730032*^9, 
  3.7659544555582695`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"04bdeb41-f15c-4d13-a3c3-\
66230530834a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"t2", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
    RowBox[{"x", ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"x", ",", "0", ",", "20", ",", "0.02"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}], 
  ";"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7659544021447754`*^9, 3.7659544078465304`*^9}, {
  3.7659547425178556`*^9, 3.765954763627802*^9}, {3.7659550199184337`*^9, 
  3.765955020580058*^9}, {3.7659551323632135`*^9, 3.7659551329149003`*^9}, {
  3.765955216729042*^9, 3.765955224438629*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[17]:=",ExpressionUUID->"54bd735f-f413-446f-b05f-621ad8bebb1f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"t3", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"t2", ",", "t1"}], "}"}], "\[Transpose]"}]}], ";"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.765954784193056*^9, 3.7659548461866503`*^9}, 
   3.7659552329867477`*^9},
 CellLabel->"In[18]:=",ExpressionUUID->"9cb5e476-2789-482a-bbd5-2f7023bec772"],

