Cell["\<\
We can try different aspect ratios for specific functions and find the best \
one that fit our needs.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766114666121603*^9, 3.7661147505843096`*^9}, {
  3.7668883398484554`*^9, 3.7668883710755453`*^9}, {3.766904164173419*^9, 
  3.7669041952103233`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2cf00272-e39f-4995-9c22-\
58226c511027"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Discontinuous Functions", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766114774097486*^9, 3.766114798749482*^9}, 
   3.766114861618103*^9},ExpressionUUID->"bc567794-2d27-4487-8fd5-\
89b947611b01"],

Cell["\<\
Not All fonctions are continuous in the domain (-\[Infinity],\[Infinity]) \
that is, some values of the dependent variable of this domain do not produce \
known values of the function. This is called ``discontinuation\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]. Discontinuation property is purely dependent of the \
configuration of the function. Functions which exhibit discontinuties are \
called ``Discontinious Functions\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] . \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7661148689634423`*^9, 3.7661150665443277`*^9}, {
   3.7661155252553525`*^9, 3.7661160907528267`*^9}, {3.766421115362158*^9, 
   3.7664212389715505`*^9}, {3.766422500951805*^9, 3.7664226134855356`*^9}, {
   3.766422753302684*^9, 3.766422767345681*^9}, {3.766422813310413*^9, 
   3.7664228587764463`*^9}, 3.7664228939703474`*^9, 3.7664229355496106`*^9, {
   3.7664230140497675`*^9, 3.7664230222410913`*^9}, {3.766423148390045*^9, 
   3.766423160731996*^9}, {3.766423234795697*^9, 3.766423270116525*^9}, 
   3.7664233032895947`*^9, {3.766888394743963*^9, 3.766888440527712*^9}, 
   3.766888475044897*^9},ExpressionUUID->"4304e046-fbd2-4077-a90a-\
cd2cc84a70cb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Most rational functions exhibit discontinuative property owing to certain \
values of x which produce ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   FractionBox["a", "0"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ef6c5633-7443-41d3-93f7-f0ed44525985"],
 " ratio, with a being a real number. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766423352157671*^9, 3.766423603013405*^9}, {
  3.7668885111192064`*^9, 
  3.766888520366925*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8671e317-8379-4c78-80ee-\
7798fc715f7d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Function discontinuity is not a simple subject to tackle at once. We should \
get proper familiarity about the discontinuties of the functions. A website \
defining concisely and comprehensibly the subject is ",
 ButtonBox["https://www.math24.net/discontinuous-functions/",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://www.math24.net/discontinuous-functions/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://www.math24.net/discontinuous-functions/"],
 " . We will follow the subject from their web pages. First discontinuity map \
devised according the definitions of this site is  presented blow:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7661256558216844`*^9, 3.7661258019138703`*^9}, {
  3.766125977949154*^9, 3.7661264029983597`*^9}, {3.766423613142619*^9, 
  3.766423638744998*^9}, {3.766424116006427*^9, 
  3.7664243713745832`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ee084392-5ce4-4320-84a1-\
89e2224f5925"],

