   BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
   Selectable->False],
  DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
  ImageSize->Automatic,
  ImageSizeRaw->{802, 670},
  PlotRange->{{0, 802}, {0, 
   670}}]], "Input",ExpressionUUID->"1ee2cca2-8383-4d58-a0fa-0e14b02e5171"]], \
"Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.7661276348653975`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"5d878b6e-dc6a-4578-97d9-\
8f6107b3932f"],

Cell["\<\
We will begin with discontinuities of first kind. The functions having \
defined limits in both sides of the point x = a , (a) being a real number in \
the domain of the function and the limits of the function are real and equal \
to each other in both sides of (a) is a function having first class removable \
discontiniuty which is not a jump discontinuation property. we will call \
these functions as ``Functions having ``A\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] type first \
class discontinuation property. Functions which exhibit jump discontinuity \
will be called as ``B\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] type first class \
discontinuation.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664250884110746`*^9, 3.76642558973876*^9}, {
   3.766425705164839*^9, 3.7664257295159316`*^9}, {3.766425773778652*^9, 
   3.766425776636021*^9}, {3.7664258402396955`*^9, 3.7664259614894485`*^9}, 
   3.7664260540246005`*^9, {3.766426096236505*^9, 3.766426096400399*^9}, {
   3.766426127680535*^9, 
   3.766426343480288*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3ab8993b-35f5-4b9a-9a1a-\
666eb8c7c64e"],

Cell["\<\
For understanding whether the function has some kind of discontinuation we \
will look at first to its graph. But careful : First class A type \
discontinuations (without a jump) can not be spotted from their graphs. \
Graphs may only reveal first class jump discontinuations (class B) and second \
kind non removable discontinuations. Then mathematical investigation in form \
of finding both side limits must be taken into account. We will follow these \
paths in examining the functions about their discontinuities. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766425972100401*^9, 3.7664260067316093`*^9}, {
  3.7664263569126177`*^9, 3.7664264690845585`*^9}, {3.766426600328674*^9, 
  3.7664273100203447`*^9}, {3.766726413348567*^9, 3.76672642989716*^9}, {
  3.766726472090174*^9, 3.76672647422396*^9}, {3.7667265618951206`*^9, 
  3.766726563605163*^9}, {3.7669042660327907`*^9, 
  3.766904345304643*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"31a74d5d-0125-4e24-8f45-\
e77bfc206890"],

Cell["\<\
Since we will need to find some limits and roots of equations, it is \
important to know, how the limits and roots of equations are found with \
Mathematica.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664273159089813`*^9, 3.7664274229228745`*^9}, {
  3.766467698745391*^9, 
  3.7664677372727685`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9738dba6-eebf-4087-9591-\
b86d0ca93375"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Limits in Mathematica", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7661277180306206`*^9, 
  3.766127738625886*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c97a0266-3097-4e6b-b12d-\
c853215e512c"],

Cell["\<\
Limits in Mathematica are found by the application of the function Limit [ ]. \
The general form of application for any function f[x] defined previously .\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664274514615655`*^9, 3.766427503125061*^9}, {
  3.766427537069674*^9, 
  3.766427603373807*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3cdfed69-c7b7-4158-b170-\
f48baba2c03e"],

Cell["Limit[f[x] , x \[Rule] a]", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766427613241189*^9, 3.7664276532503214`*^9}, 
   3.7664277255860095`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"7638b92c-1122-42f6-9624-\
6f8a1e087c78"],

Cell["\<\
For finding the lower (left) or upper (right) limit when x aproaching a,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766427732506067*^9, 3.7664278251941223`*^9}, {
  3.7664278863781796`*^9, 
  3.766427911233984*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cd6df248-892b-4a25-a14f-\
3c4c6cb09a7f"],

Cell["Limit[f[x] , x \[Rule] a-0] and Limit[f[x] , x \[Rule] a+0]", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766427613241189*^9, 3.7664276532503214`*^9}, 
   3.7664277255860095`*^9, {3.7664278576905622`*^9, 3.766427858685996*^9}, {
   3.7664279228903265`*^9, 
   3.766427943029831*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4276283f-9926-4e53-93ca-\
13b7ad2328c7"],

Cell["or,", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766428219457964*^9, 
  3.7664282246180077`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"62017b39-25e5-409d-8062-\
735b8f7fb8bd"],

Cell["\<\
Limit[f[x] , x \[Rule] a ,Direction\[Rule] -1] and Limit[f[x] , x \[Rule] a \
Direction\[Rule]1]\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664282352379503`*^9, 3.7664283373826046`*^9}, {
   3.7669230572137823`*^9, 3.766923096593336*^9}, 
   3.7669262909087105`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"2a833858-aba5-417b-bbf3-\
527b8b208038"],

Cell["\<\
Limit[f[x] , x \[Rule] a ,Direction\[Rule] -1]  means the limit of the \
function f[x] when x tends to a, approaching from above. (-1 means from +\
\[Infinity] to -\[Infinity]) or (from right to left)\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766926337712051*^9, 3.766926513532922*^9}, 
   3.766926605340619*^9},ExpressionUUID->"2fb69ddf-5614-46a1-9f03-\
5a964b6109df"],

Cell["\<\
Limit[f[x] , x \[Rule] a ,Direction\[Rule] 1]  means the limit of the \
function f[x] when x tends to a, approaching from below. (1 means from -\
\[Infinity] to 4\[Infinity]) or (from left to right).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766926337712051*^9, 3.766926513532922*^9}, {
  3.7669265652454553`*^9, 
  3.766926631721593*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"878e20ac-a376-4724-874b-\
a7d1bdec12e8"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Roots of the equations with Mathematica", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664284417590094`*^9, 
  3.7664284694421844`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"301473c9-e4af-4423-aa75-\
7d4a1ffde536"],

Cell["\<\
Mathematica include different  methods for finding the roots of equations. \
Normally using Solve [ ] function wiil be enough to spotting the roots of \
most equations. but for problematic ones, one may try more sophisticated \
functions provided form mathematica. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664285046230917`*^9, 3.7664285297627344`*^9}, 
   3.7664285624870453`*^9, {3.7664671460532255`*^9, 
   3.766467352044793*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9f28f7c1-b823-4138-aaf8-\
34d16e82d417"],

Cell["Usage of Solve function is,", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664673842187834`*^9, 
  3.766467403981616*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"88192071-856a-4c6c-9161-\
2c6c536d74df"],

Cell["\<\
Solve[f[x](== for equal, < for less than, > for greater than) right side \
term, {independentVariable}]\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664674117867694`*^9, 
  3.7664675999036317`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d338be7c-db37-4974-a8af-\
b1feb7457569"],

Cell["We are now ready for looking after the discontinuities.", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664678250559435`*^9, 
  3.7664678842895555`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"209a146a-d7aa-42fd-b585-\
bf40c721afd2"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 StyleBox["Examples", "Subsubsection"]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766428391709588*^9, 3.7664283972783976`*^9}, 
   3.766467626029668*^9, 3.7664679540898066`*^9},
 CellLabel->"In[49]:=",ExpressionUUID->"dfabf454-4d91-448c-a524-06f8b80d6f8e"],

Cell[BoxData["Examples"], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.766556470440963*^9, 3.766570319797001*^9, 
  3.7665923618038473`*^9, 3.766638124612796*^9, 3.7666442896650333`*^9, 
  3.7666753682708874`*^9, 3.7666759244158983`*^9, 3.766681996990242*^9, 
  3.766718014503251*^9, 3.766719205247961*^9, 3.7667202461162577`*^9, 
  3.7667405748943834`*^9, 3.7667501851538153`*^9, 3.7667665541401515`*^9, 
  3.7667679316105576`*^9, 3.7667680337151155`*^9, 3.766768314661027*^9, 
  3.7667684161667423`*^9, 3.766768498095414*^9, 3.7667686231315837`*^9, 
  3.766768730766243*^9, 3.7667687943276205`*^9, 3.7668865117338195`*^9, 
  3.7669026911235685`*^9, 3.766906231838133*^9, 3.766906535705061*^9, 
  3.7669068317084804`*^9, 3.7669072738766394`*^9, 3.766907339696151*^9, 
  3.766969535036997*^9, 3.766977961029315*^9, 3.7669806712118406`*^9, 
  3.7669810167639484`*^9, 3.767024134369773*^9},
 CellLabel->"Out[49]=",ExpressionUUID->"85b5db98-8b9b-4022-96dd-9d4888a81680"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["Find a discontiniuty of the function, ", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7661280765224247`*^9, 
  3.766128129941819*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"fb107045-67ce-4869-a0c4-\
d4f230da4cb7"],

Cell[TextData[Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"f", "[", "x_", "]"}], ":=", " ", 
  FractionBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"2", 
     SuperscriptBox["x", "4"]}], "-", 
    RowBox[{"12", " ", "x"}]}], 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"3", "-", 
      SuperscriptBox["x", "6"]}], ")"}], 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"1", "+", 
      SuperscriptBox["x", "4"]}], ")"}]}]]}]],
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7661161261123857`*^9, 3.7661161479532623`*^9}, {
  3.766116287470352*^9, 
  3.766116455283533*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"57fda817-46f1-4f5c-8911-\
299befe0c655"]], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.766467998799677*^9},ExpressionUUID->"f9e5a015-2bfd-4710-8c19-\
b3f8e7355451"],

Cell["Solution :", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664680257297583`*^9, 
  3.7664680562795124`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"55b1b0ca-8d19-4b2b-af59-\
4e58ad985c47"],

Cell["\<\
Altough it not fully informative about all the discontinuities \
(discontinuities of the first class type A can not be understood from the \
graph of the function) we will always begin by investigation of the graph of \
a function. Bu we will not rely completely on the primary information \
obtained form the graph for the final decision about the discontinuity of the \
function examined.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7664680770224605`*^9, 3.7664682474857855`*^9}, {
  3.7664683942970905`*^9, 3.7664684824579916`*^9}, {3.766888623959487*^9, 
  3.766888707031813*^9}, {3.7668888427029824`*^9, 3.7668889135993195`*^9}, {
  3.7668890294268646`*^9, 
  3.7668890691110992`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2570da3a-122d-47a3-94da-\
4a9c9e13877b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Clear", "[", 
  RowBox[{"f", ",", "x", ",", "n"}], "]"}]], "Input",
