Cell["\<\
This result prove that the given function has a first class A type removable \
discontinuity because limits of the both sides are numeric and equal to each \
other. This kind of discontinuity is not remarquable by plotting but with \
only by mathematical analysis.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766219683425296*^9, 3.76621971945524*^9}, {
   3.7662266451532254`*^9, 3.766226861282612*^9}, {3.7662268954305477`*^9, 
   3.766226902994896*^9}, {3.76622694380986*^9, 3.76622695500282*^9}, {
   3.7662285227021923`*^9, 3.7662285252463083`*^9}, 3.766312552658914*^9, {
   3.7664946317144365`*^9, 3.766494859371216*^9}, 3.7664952484103355`*^9, {
   3.766899339187955*^9, 3.7668993394038315`*^9}, {3.7669703523744774`*^9, 
   3.7669704427889957`*^9}, {3.766970476258051*^9, 
   3.7669704819540005`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cfbb6aa1-8531-49de-9a5e-\
a601fb41b923"],

Cell["\<\
Graphs of Mathematica can also be enhanced using options or using ``Drawing \
Tools\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] of the Mathematica. Drawings tools is \
considerably makes adding arrows, lines, text easy avoiding time consuming \
programming steps.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766227161313213*^9, 3.7662272810976343`*^9}, {
   3.76623825794587*^9, 3.766238375164853*^9}, {3.7663127809212103`*^9, 
   3.7663128528820004`*^9}, {3.7663128890183086`*^9, 3.766313076848759*^9}, {
   3.76631772390277*^9, 3.7663178351760435`*^9}, 3.76689936206783*^9, {
   3.7669260649834003`*^9, 3.7669260690750575`*^9}, {3.7669705049036894`*^9, 
   3.7669705054793825`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"82ac65eb-de20-4fa4-b90d-\
a604e1623f2f"],

Cell["\<\
Drawing Tools are supplied in recent versions of Mathematica and its use \
simplify the plot decoration, but there is constraints for using Drawings \
Tools. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766673982188197*^9, 3.7666741111472015`*^9}, {
  3.766899392808195*^9, 
  3.7668994043675637`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"167d368d-17b5-4c8f-b5bd-\
f095051ba3c8"],

Cell["\<\
Producing plots is a two step process. First step is the generation of plot \
by using predefined functions of Mathematica. The second step is to decorate \
the plot with texts, Lines, Arrows and other graphic objects. This can be \
achieved either by Graphic functions (time consuming) or Drawing Tools (fast \
and easy).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766674138787341*^9, 3.7666742077477717`*^9}, {
  3.766674248511382*^9, 3.766674432486817*^9}, {3.76689941722719*^9, 
  3.766899493944178*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d214d680-5ef0-4d73-b809-\
2115878a85b1"],

Cell["\<\
Drawing Tools is for plots which are ultimate. When the plot is \
mathematically reached at its ultimate final step, then it is more \
advantaguous to finish with Drawings Tool and save the image elsewhere for \
publishing or else.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.76667445733356*^9, 3.766674649722174*^9}, {
  3.7668995284953732`*^9, 
  3.7668996319350157`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9af4e355-7aec-4ef1-a9b6-\
ab874623c0b0"],

Cell["\<\
If we plan to further inspect by altering some options, then using graphic \
functions will be far more better, since with every new generated version of \
the plot we will have the same graphic retouches included in the program \
steps and not  by Drawings Tools. On the contrary, if we had used drawing \
tools we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll have to make same retouches with drawing tools, \
every time the new version of the graph would be produced.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7666746812950516`*^9, 3.7666749282143793`*^9}, {
  3.766674969313793*^9, 3.766675039758366*^9}, {3.7668996644353857`*^9, 
  3.7668996899227667`*^9}, {3.7669705822782*^9, 
  3.766970722287125*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"547c38d7-bebe-4d47-b340-\
55a8afb4e809"],

Cell["\<\
We will proceed by applying the required graphic add-ons by using Mathematica \
graphic functions. Adding text methods is shown below:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7663167490549765`*^9, 3.766316970531171*^9}, {
  3.7663170034762907`*^9, 3.7663170505123568`*^9}, {3.766318065271302*^9, 
  3.7663181909713087`*^9}, {3.7663182211430316`*^9, 3.7663182727145042`*^9}, {
  3.7663408550634146`*^9, 3.766340924528639*^9}, {3.7664959708231506`*^9, 
  3.766496441985885*^9}, {3.7664965861520214`*^9, 3.766496652207162*^9}, {
  3.766497261632012*^9, 3.7664972651901436`*^9}, {3.7666751454177556`*^9, 
  3.7666753251736245`*^9}, {3.7666766285120153`*^9, 
  3.766676674483647*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"badbfeb8-bf7d-495a-9598-\
51cf837c62d3"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Graphics Primitives for Text", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.766719753391542*^9},ExpressionUUID->"b327b638-8e40-45ca-b31c-\
ab6d3acc8d21"],

Cell["\<\
With the Text graphics primitive, you can insert text at any position in two \
- or three - dimensional Mathematica graphics. Unless you explicitly specify \
a style or font using Style, the text will be given in the graphic\
\[CloseCurlyQuote] s base style.
Text[expr, {x, y }]     [text centered at the point {x, y} 
Text[expr, {x, y}, {-1, 0}]      text with its left - hand end at {x, y }
Text[expr, {x, y}, {1, 0} ]        right - hand end at {x, y} 
Text[expr, {x, y}, {0, -1}]        centered above {x, y} 
Text[expr, {x, y}, {0, 1}]          centered below {x, y} 
Text[expr, {x, y}, {dx, dy}]      text positioned so that {x, y} is at \
relative coordinates {dx, dy} within the box that bounds the text
Text[expr, {x, y}, {dx, dy}, {0, 1}]        text oriented vertically to read \
from bottom to top
Text[expr, {x, y}, {dx, dy}, {0, -1}]       text that reads from top to bottom
Text[expr, {x, y}, {dx, dy}, {-1, 0}]       text that is upside - down
(\[DotlessI]n two - dimensional plots).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.766676704484455*^9, 3.766676722999818*^9}, {
  3.7667197436864557`*^9, 3.7667197475668106`*^9}, {3.766904842831266*^9, 
  3.7669048807706566`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7193994e-73e7-4fc5-b866-\
06505b449267"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It would be not so easy working with Mathematica graphic functions, if some \
previously worked examples is not at hand. A program applied below to our \
example, is shared by the University of ",
 ButtonBox["Texas",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://stat.utexas.edu/images/SSC/documents/SoftwareTutorials/\
Mathematica_Graphics.pdf"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://stat.utexas.edu/images/SSC/documents/SoftwareTutorials/\
Mathematica_Graphics.pdf"],
 " in Austin."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7666766324717445`*^9, 3.7666766346305065`*^9}, {
  3.7669110048665857`*^9, 
  3.766911004869584*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4f0ea691-27de-4a71-8f9f-\
76b4e1f19ada"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"pw1", " ", "=", 
   RowBox[{"Plot", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"f", "[", "x", "]"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"x", ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"-", "2"}], "\[Pi]"}], ",", 
       RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]"}]}], "}"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"Exclusions", "\[Rule]", 
      RowBox[{"{", "1", "}"}]}], ",", "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
     RowBox[{"Ticks", "\[Rule]", " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"{", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{"-", "2"}], "\[Pi]"}], ",", " ", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{
            RowBox[{"-", "3"}], "/", "4"}], "  ", "\[Pi]"}], ",", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{
            RowBox[{"-", "1"}], "/", "4"}], "  ", "\[Pi]"}], ",", " ", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{"1", "/", "4"}], "  ", "\[Pi]"}], ",", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{"3", "/", "4"}], "  ", "\[Pi]"}], ",", 
          RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]"}]}], "}"}], ",", "Automatic"}], "}"}]}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"ImageSize", "\[Rule]", "500"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    "]"}]}], ";"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.766495719780861*^9},
 CellLabel->"In[85]:=",ExpressionUUID->"33d385a7-3043-4b4c-b2c9-f446ea8f0f6a"],

